asm was shaped through a fusion of local patriotism and a broader imperial identity. Imperial culture was neither generic nor unimportant but was instead multi-layered and recast to capture the concerns of a locality. The book draws on a rich seam of primary sources from three representative English cities. These case studies are considered against an extensive analysis of seminal and current historiography. This renders the book invaluable to those interested in the fields of imperialism, social and cultural history, popular culture, historical geography and urban history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxHistoriography. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Catholic slum priests.  aBoer War.  aBritish Empire.  aBritish society.  aFirst World War.  acitizen-soldier relationships.  acivic culture.  acivic identity.  ahistoriography.  aimperial culture.  aimperial mission.  aimperial wars.  aimperialism.  apatriotism.  apopular culture.  areligious settlements.  aschooling.  auniversity settlements.  avolunteerism.  aworking-class children.1 aBeaven, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611755740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117557/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles